{{Infobox language |name=Mango |nativename= |states=China |ethnicity=[[Yi people|Yi]] |speakers=50 |date=2014 |ref=<ref name=Hsiu>Hsiu, Andrew. 2014. "[http://iscll-14.ling.sinica.edu.tw/files-pdf/Papers/Session2/Hsiu.pdf Mondzish: a new subgroup of Lolo-Burmese]". In ''Proceedings of the 14th International Symposium on Chinese Languages and Linguistics (IsCLL-14)''. Taipei: Academia Sinica.</ref> |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=[[Lolo-Burmese languages|Lolo-Burmese]] |fam3=[[Mondzish languages|Mondzish]] |script= |iso3=none |glotto=mang1429 |glottorefname=Mango (China) }}
'''Mango''' ([[Exonym and endonym|autonym]]: ''{{IPA|ma˨˩ŋo˨˩}}'') is a [[Lolo-Burmese languages|Lolo-Burmese language]] spoken by just under 50 people in [[Guangnan County]], [[Yunnan]], China.<ref name=Hsiu/>
Mango is spoken in the two villages of Mumei 木美 (Mango: ''{{IPA|mei˥te˧}}'') and Zhelai 者赖 (Mango: ''{{IPA|ɕi˥te˧}}''), both located in Babao Town 八宝镇 (Mango: ''{{IPA|ba˧wo˧}}'').
