{{Infobox language |name=Maza |nativename= |states=China |ethnicity=[[Yi people|Yi]] |speakers=50 |date=2014 |ref=<ref>Hsiu, Andrew. 2014. "[http://iscll-14.ling.sinica.edu.tw/files-pdf/Papers/Session2/Hsiu.pdf Mondzish: a new subgroup of Lolo-Burmese]". In ''Proceedings of the 14th International Symposium on Chinese Languages and Linguistics (IsCLL-14)''. Taipei: Academia Sinica.</ref> |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=[[Lolo-Burmese languages|Lolo-Burmese]] |fam3=[[Mondzish languages|Mondzish]] |iso3=none |glotto=maza1306 |glottorefname=Maza }}
'''Maza''' ([[Exonym and endonym|autonym]]: ''{{IPA|ma˧zɑ˥˧}}'') is a [[Lolo-Burmese languages|Lolo-Burmese language]] spoken by the [[Yi people]] of China.
Maza is spoken by about 50 people in the village of Mengmei 孟梅 (Maza: ''{{IPA|qʰa˧le˥}}''), Puyang Village 普阳村, Muyang Township 木央乡, [[Funing County, Yunnan]]. Maza has a [[Qabiao language|Qabiao]] substratum, since the area was originally inhabited by Qabiao speakers (Hsiu 2014:68-69). Maza displays [[affirmative and negative|circumfixal negation]], a syntactic feature that is usually typical of [[Kra languages]].<ref name="Hsiu2017">Hsiu, Andrew. 2017. ''[https://zenodo.org/record/1249176/files/Hezhang_Buyi_a_highly_endangered_Northern_Tai_language.pdf Hezhang Buyi: a highly endangered Northern Tai language with a Kra substratum]''. {{doi|10.5281/zenodo.1249176}}</ref>
