{{more citations needed|date=December 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}} {{Infobox university |name = Royal College of Art |image_name = Rcalogo.png |image_size = |established = {{unbulleted list|{{nobreak|1837 – Government School of Design}}|1896 – Royal College of Art}} |type = [[Public university|Public]] |rector = [[Paul Thompson (rector)|Paul Thompson]] |chancellor = Sir [[Jonathan Ive]] | students = {{HESA student population|INSTID=0003}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name="HESA citation">{{HESA citation}}</ref> |city = [[London]] |country = United Kingdom |campus = [[Urban area|Urban]] |website = {{url|www.rca.ac.uk}} }}
The '''Royal College of Art''' ('''RCA''') is a [[public university|public]] [[research university]] in [[London]], in the United Kingdom. It offers [[postgraduate degree]]s in [[art]] and [[design]] to students from over 60 countries;<ref name="Review">{{cite journal|title=RCA Annual Review 2013/2014|pages=4–5|url=http://www.rca.ac.uk/documents/444/RCA.ANN.14.WEB.8.pdf|accessdate=2 May 2015}}</ref> it is the only entirely postgraduate art and design university in the world.{{r|alice|page=118}} From 2015 onwards, the RCA has consistently placed first in the [[QS World University Rankings]] in the Art and Design subject area.<ref>{{cite web|last1=RCA|title=Royal College of Art is the World’s Best University for Art & Design for Consecutive Year|url=https://www.rca.ac.uk/news-and-events/press-releases/royal-college-art-worlds-best-university-art-design-consecutive-year/|website=RCA|accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Aimée|title=RCA tops world rankings of art and design universities|url=https://www.designweek.co.uk/issues/6-12-march-2017/rca-tops-world-rankings-art-design-universities/|website=Design Week|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=RCA|title=Royal College of Art is the World’s Best University for Art & Design for Consecutive Year|url=https://www.rca.ac.uk/news-and-events/news/rca-worlds-top-university-art-design-fourth-year/|website=RCA|accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/universities/royal-college-art|website=QS World University Rankings|accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref>
==History== The RCA was founded in [[Somerset House]] in 1837 as the '''Government School of Design'''{{r|aim25}} or '''Metropolitan School of Design'''.{{r|riba}} [[Richard Burchett]] became head of the school in 1852.{{r|dnb}} In 1853 it was expanded and moved to [[Marlborough House]], and then, in 1853{{r|aim25}} or 1857,{{r|riba|dnb}} to [[South Kensington]], on the same site as the [[South Kensington Museum]]. It was renamed the '''Normal Training School of Art''' in 1857{{r|riba}} and the '''National Art Training School''' in 1863.{{r|dnb}} During the later 19th century it was primarily a [[teacher training college]]; pupils during this period included [[George Clausen]], [[Christopher Dresser]], [[Luke Fildes]], [[Kate Greenaway]] and [[Gertrude Jekyll]].{{r|dnb}}
In 1896{{r|aim25}} or 1897{{r|riba}} the school received the name '''Royal College of Art''', and the emphasis of teaching there shifted to the practice of art and design.<ref name=aim25/> Teaching of [[graphic design]], [[industrial design]] and [[product design]] began in the mid-twentieth century. The school expanded further in the 1960s, and in 1967 it received a [[Royal Charter]] which gave it the status of an independent university with the power to grant its own degrees.<ref name=aim25/>
==Campuses== [[File:Darwin Building, Royal College of Art in London, spring 2013.JPG|thumb|right|The Darwin Building in [[Kensington Gore]]]]
The RCA has two campuses, in [[South Kensington]] and in [[Battersea]].{{r|rca}} The Darwin Building in [[Kensington Gore]] dates from the 1960s and is a Grade II [[listed building]]. It was designed by a team of RCA staff members, [[H. T. Cadbury-Brown]], [[Hugh Casson]] and Robert Goodden.<ref name=dunnett/>
In 1991 the [[sculpture]] department moved to a converted factory across the river [[Thames]] in Battersea. In the early 2000s the college conceived a substantial second campus being created on the site, with a minibus service linking it to Kensington. Thus, after a successful redevelopment of the premises by [[Wright & Wright]] (budget £4.3m, floor area 2,500 sq m), the present Sculpture Building opened in January 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal College of Art Sculpture Building officially reopens|url=http://www.rca.ac.uk/news-and-events/news/rca-sculpture-building-officially-reopens/|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bizley|first1=Graham|title=Wright & Wright's RCA sculpture department refurb|url=http://www.bdonline.co.uk/wright-and-wright%E2%80%99s-rca-sculpture-department-refurb/3131922.article|publisher=BD online 23 January 2009|accessdate=6 October 2015}}{{subscription required}}</ref>
A masterplan was commissioned by [[Haworth Tompkins]] and phase 1 of their three phase design was completed with the opening of the Sackler Building on 19 November 2009, to house the painting department. Its name commemorates a major gift by [[Mortimer Sackler|The Dr Mortimer and Theresa Sackler Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The new RCA Painting Building is now open|url=http://www.rca.ac.uk/news-and-events/news/the-new-rca-painting-building-is-now-open/|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Sackler Building by Haworth Tompkins|url=http://www.dezeen.com/2009/12/02/the-sackler-building-by-haworth-tompkins/|publisher=Dezeen 2 December 2009|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=RCA Sackler Building|url=https://vimeo.com/7822996|publisher=AJ Building Study video|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>
The Dyson Building, named in honour of [[James Dyson]], whose educational charity donated £5m to the development, was opened on 24 September 2012. It is the home for [[printmaking]] and [[photography]], and contains an innovation wing where start-up designers can launch their businesses.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Dyson Building by Haworth Tompkins|url=http://www.dezeen.com/2012/09/28/the-dyson-building-by-haworth-tompkins/|publisher=Dezeen 28 September 2012|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hunter|first1=Will|title=Royal College of Art by Haworth Tompkins|url=http://www.architectural-review.com/buildings/london-schools-part-one-royal-college-of-art-by-haworth-tompkins/8643316.article|publisher=AR online 27 February 2013|accessdate=6 October 2015}}{{subscription required}}</ref>
The Woo Building was opened on 30 September 2015, completing the Battersea project. It is named in honour of [[Woo Po-shing|Sir Po-Shing and Lady Helen Woo]], who have funded scholarships at the RCA since the 1990s. It accommodates the Ceramics & Glass and Jewellery & Metal programmes. The building's [[Anodizing|anodised aluminium]] gates were designed by alumnus Max Lamb.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jordan|first1=Sarah|title=RCA opens state of the art Woo Building for jewellery and silversmithing students|url=http://www.retail-jeweller.com/business/rca-opens-state-of-the-art-woo-building-for-jewellery-students/5079631.article|publisher=Retail Jeweller 2 October 2015|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=New Gates installed for the opening of the Woo Building Battersea|url=http://www.rca.ac.uk/news-and-events/news/new-gates-installed-opening-woo-building-battersea/|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>
==Courses== The RCA offers Graduate Diploma, [[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Master of Philosophy|MRes, MPhil]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] degrees in twenty-eight subject areas, divided into four schools: [[architecture]], arts & humanities, [[communication]], and [[design]]. The [[history of design]] programme is in collaboration with the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]]; there are two double MA/[[Master of Science|MSc]] programmes in [[design engineering]] with [[Imperial College London]], one of which also includes periods of study at [[Keio University]] in Tokyo and at the [[Pratt Institute]] in New York.{{r|rca2}}
==Rankings== In the [[Research Assessment Exercise]] of December 2008, 40% of the research output of the school received the highest (4* or "world-leading") assessment, the third-highest rating in the art and design subject area; over all subject areas only about fifty institutions received a higher rating.{{r|rae}}
In April 2011 the RCA was ranked first on a list of UK graduate art schools compiled by ''[[Modern Painters (magazine)|Modern Painters]]'' magazine from a survey of professionals in the art world.{{r|city}}
In August 2015 it was ranked first on a list of master's courses in fashion by Business of Fashion, a fashion website.{{r|guard2|bof}}
In 2015 the RCA placed first in the art and design subject area in the [[QS World University Rankings]] published by [[Quacquarelli Symonds]]. In 2016 and 2017 it held onto the position, increasing its overall score from 96.0/100 to 98.4/100.{{r|guard|qs}}
==Alumni== {{main|List of alumni of the Royal College of Art}} {{See also|Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Art}}
The Royal College of Art and its predecessor schools have numerous notable alumni in many fields.
Among those who studied in the predecessor schools in the nineteenth century were Sir [[George Clausen]], [[Christopher Dresser]], Sir [[Luke Fildes]], [[Kate Greenaway]], [[Gertrude Jekyll]]{{r|dnb}} and [[Edwin Lutyens]].
Alumni from the twentieth and twenty-first centuries include the sculptors [[Barbara Hepworth]] and [[Henry Moore]], painters [[Frank Auerbach]], [[David Hockney]], [[Bridget Riley]], [[Peter Blake (artist)|Sir Peter Blake]] and [[Charles Tunnicliffe]], artists [[Jake and Dinos Chapman]], [[Tracey Emin]] and [[R. B. Kitaj]], fashion designers [[Ossie Clark]] and [[Zandra Rhodes]], industrial designers [[James Dyson]] and [[David Mellor (cutler)|David Mellor]], film directors [[Tony Scott|Tony]] and [[Ridley Scott]], the designer [[Thomas Heatherwick]], prominent member of the suffragette movement [[Sylvia Pankhurst]], the musician [[Ian Dury]] and the actor [[Alan Rickman]].
See also: '''[http://www.rcasociety.net/home The Royal College of Art Society]''' amalgamated with OSARCA (the Old Students Association of the RCA 1912) for the benefit of graduates and associates of the Royal College of Art
==Awards and prizes== The Royal College of Art has several awards and prizes which it confers on its graduating students. These include the [[Sheila Robinson|Sheila Robinson Drawing Prize]].
